WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
And now, please, let's welcome Ian Cook.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Hi, good afternoon.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
So 2020, this year, marks the 50th birthday of SQL.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.240
SQL, or S-Q-L, if you prefer, is, of course, the database query language that's ubiquitous

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:26.760
today.

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:33.040
Its origins date back to 1970, when Edgar F. Codd at IBM published this seminal paper

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:36.119
that established the theoretical basis for SQL.

00:00:36.119 --> 00:00:39.840
It took a few more years after this, actually, before the language as we know it today came

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:40.840
into being.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:42.520
R, by comparison, is younger.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:47.279
The first version dates back to the early 90s, although its precursor, S, also dates

00:00:47.279 --> 00:00:49.880
back to the 70s.

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:51.200
So let's do a show of hands.

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:53.840
Raise your hand if you know at least some SQL.

00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:54.840
If you've used it...

00:00:54.840 --> 00:00:55.840
Okay.

00:00:55.919 --> 00:00:57.919
Raise your hand if you're in the room, is a little bit familiar, at least, with SQL.

00:00:57.919 --> 00:00:59.200
So put your hands down.

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:05.400
And second question, now raise your hand if you learned SQL before you learned R. Okay.

00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:09.959
Most people in this room, even here at an R conference, it seems like most people learned

00:01:09.959 --> 00:01:13.379
SQL first, or at least a good share.

00:01:13.379 --> 00:01:19.919
In the broader population, vastly more people use SQL than R. And most people who use R

00:01:19.919 --> 00:01:22.680
learn SQL first.

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:27.680
If you work in industry, especially, you'll often see lots of anecdotal evidence for this.

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:32.360
And it's borne out by things like the Stack Overflow developer survey results.

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:37.639
So my story with R and SQL is I first learned R in graduate school for statistics.

00:01:37.639 --> 00:01:41.980
But then when I finished my degree and started working in industry, I started having to use

00:01:41.980 --> 00:01:43.040
SQL a lot.

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:46.680
And I've used both R and SQL a great deal ever since.

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:52.639
But over the last year or so, I really leveled up my SQL when I created a SQL-focused Coursera

00:01:52.639 --> 00:01:53.760
course.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:57.959
So there's me on video teaching the Coursera learners about a particular aggregate function

00:01:57.959 --> 00:01:59.500
in SQL.

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:01.760
Can you guess which one it is?

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:02.760
Based on my costume.

00:02:02.760 --> 00:02:03.760
Come on.

00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:04.760
Count.

00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:05.760
Yes.

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:07.360
It's a fun course, by the way.

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:08.360
You can check it out.

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:11.399
There's a link to it in my Twitter bio.

00:02:11.399 --> 00:02:17.399
So if you know some SQL and you know R and the tidyverse, one of the things you'll notice

00:02:17.399 --> 00:02:23.720
is that SQL and dplyr are really like two implementations of the same abstract concept.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:26.800
And they have a whole lot in common.

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:32.199
First of all, a table in SQL is essentially equivalent to the concept of a tidy data frame

00:02:32.199 --> 00:02:35.759
in R. So each variable forms a column.

00:02:35.759 --> 00:02:37.479
Each observation forms a row.

00:02:37.479 --> 00:02:41.300
Each type of observational unit forms a table.

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:46.979
That's what we call tidy data in R. But in the world of SQL, that is really the essence

00:02:46.979 --> 00:02:52.179
of Edgar F. Codd's third normal form, which is the most widely used way of structuring

00:02:52.179 --> 00:02:55.419
the tables in a database.

00:02:55.419 --> 00:02:59.699
And once you have your data in this kind of structure, whether you call it tidy or third

00:02:59.699 --> 00:03:04.740
normal form, the types of operations you can apply to the data are basically the same in

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:07.339
dplyr as in SQL.

00:03:07.339 --> 00:03:13.139
So dplyr, as I'm sure most of us know, provides a set of functions, so-called verbs.

00:03:13.139 --> 00:03:17.899
And the idea is that you can use just a few of these to do most of the kinds of data manipulation

00:03:17.899 --> 00:03:19.619
that you'd ever need to do.

00:03:19.619 --> 00:03:24.820
So when Hadley created dplyr, essentially what he did was he took the semantics of the

00:03:24.820 --> 00:03:30.619
SQL SELECT statement and he brought it into R. Of course, the syntax is different, and

00:03:30.619 --> 00:03:33.699
Hadley did depart from SQL in a few notable ways.

00:03:33.699 --> 00:03:36.339
But the similarities are really striking.

00:03:36.339 --> 00:03:40.979
So if you're familiar with SQL, then you'll recall the clauses of the SQL SELECT statement.

00:03:40.979 --> 00:03:45.899
SELECT FROM, WHERE, GROUP BY, HAVING, ORDER BY, and LIMIT are the main clauses.

00:03:45.899 --> 00:03:49.500
And each of these maps onto a dplyr verb.

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:52.339
But it's not exactly a clean one-to-one mapping.

00:03:52.339 --> 00:03:53.940
So let me go through this.

00:03:53.940 --> 00:03:58.899
The FROM clause in SQL, I'll start there, just specifies what table to use.

00:03:58.899 --> 00:04:02.740
So in dplyr, you do that by specifying just the name of a data frame.

00:04:02.740 --> 00:04:06.259
Of course, you have to load the data in or point to it.

00:04:06.259 --> 00:04:11.259
Of course, in the case of using multiple tables with a join, it's a bit different.

00:04:11.259 --> 00:04:15.619
The SELECT statement in SQL has several different roles.

00:04:15.619 --> 00:04:18.140
The SELECT LIST, I should say.

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:21.899
So it corresponds to different dplyr verbs, depending on what you're trying to do.

00:04:21.899 --> 00:04:26.820
If you're just grabbing existing columns, then that's a SELECT in dplyr.

00:04:26.820 --> 00:04:32.500
If you're using expressions to define new columns, that's MUTATE or TRANSMUTE.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:37.619
And if you're using aggregate functions, in that case, SELECT corresponds to SUMMARIZE

00:04:37.619 --> 00:04:39.980
in dplyr.

00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:44.619
The WHERE clause in a SQL SELECT statement corresponds to FILTER.

00:04:44.619 --> 00:04:49.260
GROUP BY corresponds very nicely to GROUP BY.

00:04:49.260 --> 00:04:55.059
HAVING in SQL, that's the clause that you use to filter by groups after aggregating.

00:04:55.059 --> 00:05:02.019
And in dplyr, you would use FILTER for that, but you'd use it after GROUP BY.

00:05:02.019 --> 00:05:06.059
And then ORDER BY, that corresponds to ARRANGE in dplyr.

00:05:06.059 --> 00:05:11.660
And finally, LIMIT, that's just HEAD or SLICE, if you prefer.

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:15.739
And incidentally, you know, it's not just dplyr and SQL that have this same underlying

00:05:15.739 --> 00:05:17.420
abstraction layer.

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:20.779
This has proven to be such a successful one that it's been widely adopted.

00:05:20.779 --> 00:05:26.079
Pandas and Python, Spark in the big data world, many, many more tools for working with data

00:05:26.079 --> 00:05:28.980
all follow the same semantics to varying degrees.

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:31.779
I mean, some, like dplyr, adopted it from the start.

00:05:31.779 --> 00:05:34.619
Others kind of backfitted to it later.

00:05:34.619 --> 00:05:40.700
Anyway, one of the great things about this common abstraction underlying both SQL and

00:05:40.700 --> 00:05:47.459
dplyr is that it's enabled dplyr code to be translated into SQL, allowing you to use dplyr

00:05:47.459 --> 00:05:49.059
to query databases.

00:05:49.059 --> 00:05:53.059
And this is enabled by the package dbplyr.

00:05:53.059 --> 00:05:58.019
With dbplyr, you can connect to a database, refer to a specific table in the database,

00:05:58.019 --> 00:06:03.220
and then chain on dplyr verbs, just as if you were working with an in-memory R dataframe.

00:06:03.220 --> 00:06:09.059
And what dbplyr does is it translates all those dplyr operations into a SQL SELECT statement,

00:06:09.059 --> 00:06:12.940
sometimes with the help of a custom backend package, like, specific to that, you know,

00:06:12.940 --> 00:06:13.940
SQL engine.

00:06:13.940 --> 00:06:19.260
And then finally, it uses the DBI package to run that SQL SELECT statement on the database

00:06:19.260 --> 00:06:23.380
and return the result back to R. So just to show...

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:24.899
This is kind of small.

00:06:24.899 --> 00:06:30.220
If you can't see the slides, they're in my GitHub repo at enmcook on GitHub.

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:32.140
So sorry about the size.

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:34.459
But here's an example of how dbplyr works.

00:06:34.459 --> 00:06:36.619
So you first define a variable.

00:06:36.619 --> 00:06:40.100
It's effectively just a pointer to a database table.

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:41.100
And then here's a...

00:06:41.100 --> 00:06:46.059
Oh, so in this example, this is just creating a small in-memory SQLite database, and then

00:06:46.059 --> 00:06:49.220
it's copying the iris dataframe to it.

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:54.859
Then you can use dplyr on that table in the SQL engine, just as if it were an in-memory

00:06:54.859 --> 00:06:55.859
dataframe.

00:06:55.859 --> 00:07:02.660
And if you're ever curious about what SQL code your dplyr code is being translated into,

00:07:02.660 --> 00:07:09.459
dbplyr has a handy function, show query, that will show you the SQL that it's generating.

00:07:09.459 --> 00:07:12.220
So I've been using dbplyr for several years.

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:16.260
I've made a few small contributions to it, and I developed a custom backend package for

00:07:16.260 --> 00:07:17.260
it.

00:07:17.260 --> 00:07:20.660
But I've always wondered, like, what about going in the other direction?

00:07:20.660 --> 00:07:24.420
What about translating SQL to dplyr code?

00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:27.140
I always thought it would be really cool to have this.

00:07:27.140 --> 00:07:31.260
It could enable you to use SQL statements to query dataframes in R. And I searched all

00:07:31.260 --> 00:07:36.579
around, and there was no existing package that did quite this, SQL to dplyr translation.

00:07:36.579 --> 00:07:38.980
And I wondered, like, well, why is that?

00:07:38.980 --> 00:07:44.700
Is it because translating SQL to dplyr is just a really hard problem, so no one's undertaking

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:45.700
it?

00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:49.940
Or is it because everyone is so happy to write dplyr code to manipulate data that no one

00:07:49.940 --> 00:07:53.660
wants to be able to use SQL to query dataframes?

00:07:53.899 --> 00:07:58.459
Well, there's a clear answer to this question, evidenced by the popularity of another R package,

00:07:58.459 --> 00:07:59.459
sqldf.

00:07:59.459 --> 00:08:02.299
So this is a well-established package.

00:08:02.299 --> 00:08:06.619
It's very popular, created by this guy, Gabor Grotendijk.

00:08:06.619 --> 00:08:10.220
And it lets you run SQL queries on R dataframes.

00:08:10.220 --> 00:08:13.299
But to do this, it does not parse your SQL statement.

00:08:13.299 --> 00:08:15.739
Instead, it uses a clever trick.

00:08:15.739 --> 00:08:19.100
The package includes an embedded database.

00:08:19.100 --> 00:08:24.299
And it loads your R dataframe into the database, and then runs SQL queries on the database,

00:08:24.299 --> 00:08:28.140
and then returns the result as an R dataframe.

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:30.299
So here's an example of sqldf at work.

00:08:30.299 --> 00:08:34.380
The main function has the same name as the package, sqldf.

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:38.859
And you pass it just one argument, which is a SQL statement enclosed in quotes.

00:08:38.859 --> 00:08:43.179
And the one part of this SQL statement that it does look at is the from clause to identify

00:08:43.179 --> 00:08:48.979
which dataframes, you know, you're referring to, and it loads those into the database.

00:08:48.979 --> 00:08:51.859
But it doesn't do any further parsing of the SQL statement.

00:08:51.859 --> 00:08:55.700
It just passes it over to the database to run.

00:08:55.700 --> 00:08:57.820
I think sqldf is really cool.

00:08:57.820 --> 00:09:02.260
It eliminates an obstacle for users who are proficient in SQL and not so proficient in

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:06.140
dplyr, and who just need to get some data manipulation done in R.

00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:10.859
So I work as a data science and machine learning educator at Cloudera.

00:09:10.859 --> 00:09:14.419
And I encounter a lot of learners who just love this, they eat it up.

00:09:14.419 --> 00:09:18.619
They typically have some experience with SQL, and they're really excited that they can reuse

00:09:18.659 --> 00:09:23.619
those skills inside R to do the kind of boring data manipulation piece, and they can move

00:09:23.619 --> 00:09:28.340
on to the more exciting stuff, like machine learning and ggplot2 and shiny apps, which

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:32.059
were, you know, the reasons they were excited to learn R in the first place.

00:09:32.059 --> 00:09:37.859
But there are a couple of fundamental limitations to sqldf, just inherent to the way it works,

00:09:37.859 --> 00:09:39.739
that it's important to recognize.

00:09:39.739 --> 00:09:43.700
Like I said, it works by copying data out of R into a database.

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:46.419
That's okay for smaller, maybe medium-sized data.

00:09:46.419 --> 00:09:50.340
It does introduce a bit of latency on the first query for a particular data frame, because

00:09:50.340 --> 00:09:52.219
it has to copy it.

00:09:52.219 --> 00:09:55.260
But subsequent queries are pretty fast on the same data.

00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:59.659
However, with bigger data, it could be really impractical to make a copy like this.

00:09:59.659 --> 00:10:04.500
Just like architecturally, copying data to a whole different system like this seems like

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:05.500
a bit of an anti-pattern.

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:10.140
It's a clever approach, for sure, but it's a bit of a shortcut solution to the problem,

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:14.000
and I have some qualms with that way of doing it.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:20.119
Second thing, what sqldf provides feels less like a bridge from SQL to R and more like

00:10:20.119 --> 00:10:21.119
a dead end.

00:10:21.119 --> 00:10:25.640
I mean, you could just, you know, refuse to learn dplyr and just do all your data manipulation

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:27.640
in R using SQL.

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:28.640
This just feels wrong to me.

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:32.719
I mean, I think it's important to learn dplyr at some point.

00:10:32.719 --> 00:10:37.119
So a few months ago, I set out to create something that doesn't have these shortcomings, and

00:10:37.119 --> 00:10:41.760
it was immediately apparent to me that this problem breaks down into two separate pieces.

00:10:41.760 --> 00:10:47.479
One, parsing a SQL query into some kind of abstract representation of the data manipulation

00:10:47.479 --> 00:10:49.479
specified in the query.

00:10:49.479 --> 00:10:56.320
And then two, actually applying those data manipulation steps to the data in R data frames.

00:10:56.320 --> 00:11:00.900
So the first challenge then was to create a SQL query parser for R. I mean, how hard

00:11:00.900 --> 00:11:01.900
could that be?

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:04.080
It turns out it's pretty hard.

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:09.280
So to achieve it, I ended up building kind of a Rube Goldberg machine.

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:14.159
I created this package called QueryParser, and it's on CRAN.

00:11:14.159 --> 00:11:17.599
The main function in QueryParser is named parseQuery.

00:11:17.599 --> 00:11:22.960
It takes a quoted SQL SELECT statement as input, and what it returns is a list with

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:27.880
sublists that are named according to the structure of the SELECT statement.

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:31.960
So you can see in this example, using the iris table, the SQL statement has a SELECT

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:36.979
clause, a FROM clause, and a GROUP BY clause, and the list returned by parseQuery has sublists

00:11:36.979 --> 00:11:39.159
that are named the same.

00:11:39.159 --> 00:11:45.400
And then the items within the sublists, what they are are unevaluated R expressions.

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:49.640
In this example, see how there are two expressions in the SELECT list in the SQL query?

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:53.799
One returns the species column, one computes the average of the sepal length column for

00:11:53.799 --> 00:11:54.799
each species.

00:11:54.799 --> 00:11:59.239
And these have been translated from SQL to R, and they're each returned within the SELECT

00:11:59.239 --> 00:12:02.200
sublist as an unevaluated R expression.

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:05.960
And there are also some attributes in this list indicating various properties, like whether

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:08.359
the query aggregates.

00:12:08.359 --> 00:12:11.479
So I'm really proud of a few things about how QueryParser works.

00:12:11.479 --> 00:12:17.640
One, it is implemented entirely as R code, with no imports, no depends, no compiled code.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:20.880
It's just R code calling base R functions.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:22.520
And this makes it easy to maintain.

00:12:22.520 --> 00:12:25.400
No dependencies are gonna break over time.

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:33.200
However, there is an option in this function to use functions from several tidyverse packages

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:36.280
in the translations that it outputs.

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:39.119
This option defaults to false, but you can set it to true.

00:12:39.119 --> 00:12:44.000
So in this example, for instance, COUNTSTAR translates to the dplyr function n to count

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.760
the number of rows, which is handy in many cases.

00:12:48.760 --> 00:12:53.400
QueryParser performs semantic translations, not literal translations.

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:58.719
And a good example of this is how it translates the SQL aggregate expression SUM of 1.

00:12:58.719 --> 00:13:02.440
This is commonly used by folks in the SQL community just to count rows.

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:05.159
It does the same thing as COUNTSTAR.

00:13:05.159 --> 00:13:07.880
But the SUM function in R doesn't work like that.

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:12.400
So QueryParser translates this to the dplyr n function.

00:13:12.400 --> 00:13:19.119
Also, the parseQuery function checks all the expressions in all the clauses of the query

00:13:19.119 --> 00:13:23.359
that you pass to it against a list of allowed functions and operators.

00:13:23.359 --> 00:13:27.320
And it throws an error like this if there's a function or operator that's not on that

00:13:27.320 --> 00:13:28.320
list.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:30.760
And the reason I did this is because I'm imagining that someone will eventually build this into

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:36.119
a shiny app where there's a box that allows users to input a SQL query.

00:13:36.119 --> 00:13:41.359
And in this case, QueryParser would allow any malicious inputs from getting through.

00:13:41.359 --> 00:13:44.760
So the details about how all this works are enough to fill a whole different talk.

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:46.400
So I'm not going to describe them all.

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:49.640
But in the simplest sense, it kind of goes like this.

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:52.200
First, it splits the query into clauses.

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:57.559
Then it splits the clauses into strings containing different SQL expressions.

00:13:57.559 --> 00:14:03.440
And then it manipulates the strings to change them from SQL expressions to R-ish expressions.

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:07.320
Things that R will recognize as R code.

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:11.239
This is the most laborious and unsatisfying part of the whole process.

00:14:11.239 --> 00:14:16.400
The code in QueryParser needs to step through every single expression, character by character,

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:20.719
keeping track of when it's inside quotes, when it's inside parentheses, looking for

00:14:20.719 --> 00:14:24.280
different kinds of SQL syntax and replacing them with the equivalent R syntax.

00:14:24.359 --> 00:14:28.520
It uses this thing called raw connections inside base R to do that.

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:32.159
It's not particularly elegant, but it works.

00:14:32.159 --> 00:14:40.380
The next step is it takes those R-like expressions and it parses them using str2lang, which creates

00:14:40.380 --> 00:14:46.520
an unevaluated R expression from a string containing R code.

00:14:46.520 --> 00:14:49.840
And now this is the step that is satisfying.

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:55.919
After that, what happens is this magical combination of quoting, substitution, unquoting, deparsing,

00:14:55.919 --> 00:14:57.119
string manipulation, reparsing.

00:14:57.119 --> 00:15:02.440
Some of this is what you might call quasi-quotation in an Rlang context.

00:15:02.440 --> 00:15:07.359
But here it's all done with base R. And this is the part that I'd love to do a whole talk

00:15:07.359 --> 00:15:09.719
about, because it's sort of fascinating how it all works.

00:15:09.719 --> 00:15:13.840
After that, I have to do a few more manipulations of the abstract syntax tree to make everything

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:15.320
work exactly right.

00:15:15.919 --> 00:15:20.840
Then I perform some basic validity checks and then return that list that you saw in

00:15:20.840 --> 00:15:22.200
the previous slide.

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:27.619
So all this takes about only 100 milliseconds for a simple query.

00:15:27.619 --> 00:15:30.840
Maybe like 200 or 300 milliseconds for a more complex query.

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:32.359
It could be much faster, for sure.

00:15:32.359 --> 00:15:37.280
But to the end user, just parsing one query, it feels instantaneous.

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:39.799
So moving on to the second piece, tidyquery.

00:15:39.799 --> 00:15:41.359
This is also on CRAN.

00:15:41.359 --> 00:15:45.960
And this is the package that most end users will actually use.

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:49.280
The main function in tidyquery is named query.

00:15:49.280 --> 00:15:53.840
It takes a quoted select statement as input, and it uses the from clause to identify which

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:55.679
data frame you want to query.

00:15:55.679 --> 00:16:00.440
And then it uses the rest of the select statement to establish how to manipulate that data frame,

00:16:00.440 --> 00:16:04.200
performs those manipulations, and returns a new data frame as the result.

00:16:04.200 --> 00:16:09.460
So basically, if you're familiar with SQLDF, then you use tidyquery just the same way.

00:16:09.460 --> 00:16:13.700
But of course, it works differently under the hood, as I'll describe.

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:15.340
But first, there's another option.

00:16:15.340 --> 00:16:21.820
You can also use this query function like a dplyr verb in a chain with other dplyr verbs

00:16:21.820 --> 00:16:24.140
above it and below it.

00:16:24.140 --> 00:16:26.940
The thing is, you just have to leave out the from clause.

00:16:26.940 --> 00:16:33.760
Because then the data that's passed in, piped in above, becomes the from clause.

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:39.219
So despite the syntax of this being similar to SQLDF, under the hood, this query function

00:16:39.979 --> 00:16:41.419
in tidyquery works totally differently.

00:16:41.419 --> 00:16:46.659
The first thing it does is it calls the parse query function in query parser.

00:16:46.659 --> 00:16:51.539
Then getting back that list, it determines which sequence of dplyr verbs it needs to

00:16:51.539 --> 00:16:54.780
call to execute this query.

00:16:54.780 --> 00:17:00.340
And then it uses dplyr with the help of rlang to evaluate the expressions in the context

00:17:00.340 --> 00:17:01.919
of a data frame.

00:17:01.919 --> 00:17:05.300
So I should say, tidyquery has lots of dependencies.

00:17:05.300 --> 00:17:07.420
Query parser is the one that's got no dependencies.

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:14.699
Tidyquery has lots of dependencies, including rlang and dplyr, of course.

00:17:14.699 --> 00:17:19.380
So if you remember the earlier slide about dbplyr, essentially, tidyquery is like the

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:22.819
inverse of dbplyr, which Hadley was quick to note.

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:25.819
I'm not sure how you say dbplyr backwards.

00:17:25.819 --> 00:17:28.819
I'm not gonna try.

00:17:28.819 --> 00:17:32.300
Currently query parser and tidyquery work for the most common types of SQL queries.

00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:34.500
They have some limitations.

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:37.459
I'll not go through these point by point in the interest of time.

00:17:37.459 --> 00:17:40.540
But I do have plans to implement all of this.

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:42.859
But I don't have any specific time frames yet.

00:17:42.859 --> 00:17:47.739
If you feel strongly that you'd like to see one of these features implemented sooner rather

00:17:47.739 --> 00:17:48.739
than later, let me know.

00:17:48.739 --> 00:17:53.180
And I've talked to several people at the conference who voted for subqueries.

00:17:53.180 --> 00:17:57.719
But find the relevant GitHub issue at one of those links.

00:17:57.719 --> 00:17:58.719
And let me know.

00:17:58.719 --> 00:18:01.219
Give it a thumbs up if that's the feature you'd like to see.

00:18:01.219 --> 00:18:05.780
And also, if you try these packages and you notice that something's broken or if it's

00:18:05.780 --> 00:18:10.819
missing a translation for some function that you want it to use, just create an issue.

00:18:10.819 --> 00:18:11.819
Include a reprex.

00:18:11.819 --> 00:18:16.260
And I'd love to take a look at that.

00:18:16.260 --> 00:18:21.300
So one of the things I'm really excited about is that tidyquery doesn't work only on R dataframes.

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:24.939
It can work on any data object that dbplyr can work on.

00:18:24.939 --> 00:18:27.359
So for example, data.table.

00:18:27.359 --> 00:18:33.000
With Hadley's recent overhaul of the dtplyr package, you can use dplyr code with data.table

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.880
and it uses lazy evaluation to run efficiently on data.table.

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:40.439
So tidyquery preserves that lazy evaluation.

00:18:40.439 --> 00:18:43.319
And here's an example that works just like the last one.

00:18:43.319 --> 00:18:47.839
You just have to call that lazy dt function at the beginning to create that data.table

00:18:47.839 --> 00:18:49.719
layer.

00:18:49.719 --> 00:18:53.839
So basically any time dplyr works with some data source, tidyquery can work with it.

00:18:53.839 --> 00:18:57.400
Maybe I might have to make a couple little changes to recognize the class name.

00:18:57.400 --> 00:18:59.000
But it'll all work.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:00.000
And it won't move the data.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:01.959
It'll query it in place.

00:19:01.959 --> 00:19:06.040
I'm excited to try this with the new version of the Apache arrow R package that Neil Richardson

00:19:06.040 --> 00:19:08.839
spoke about yesterday, which now supports dplyr verbs.

00:19:08.839 --> 00:19:11.640
I haven't tried it, but I'll do that soon.

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:14.560
There's one more thing about tidyquery that I'm really excited about.

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:21.239
So besides running your SQL query, tidyquery can also show you the dplyr code that it translated

00:19:21.239 --> 00:19:22.959
your query into.

00:19:23.079 --> 00:19:27.160
So to do this, you use the function show underscore query.

00:19:27.160 --> 00:19:28.160
And here's a simple example.

00:19:28.160 --> 00:19:33.839
This is exactly the same dplyr code that would run if you were to call the query function.

00:19:33.839 --> 00:19:39.400
And internally, there's actually just one main function that runs query and show dplyr.

00:19:39.400 --> 00:19:43.199
And that function has a great deal of conditional logic to try to generate the simplest possible

00:19:43.199 --> 00:19:45.719
dplyr code that it can, given your query.

00:19:45.719 --> 00:19:50.640
So the dplyr code ends up being basically what you would get if you wrote it, you know,

00:19:50.640 --> 00:19:52.199
as a human.

00:19:52.199 --> 00:19:54.040
And here's a more complex example.

00:19:54.040 --> 00:19:58.239
Lest you think I'm cherry-picking simple examples that will work, no, it can generate some really

00:19:58.239 --> 00:20:00.239
complicated queries with joins and so forth.

00:20:00.239 --> 00:20:03.719
And I think for a lot of people, being able to see instant translations from a language

00:20:03.719 --> 00:20:08.680
they do understand to one they don't is a really effective means of learning a new language.

00:20:08.680 --> 00:20:12.579
So I hope that this provides a valuable learning and teaching tool and helps build the bridge

00:20:12.579 --> 00:20:14.680
from SQL to R. Thank you.

